(3370, 'DonaldCloda', 'doloreswhitton1912@salpingomyu.ru', '89185717638', '-', '-', 'лњлЙлхлйлйЛІл╣ л░л┤л▓лЙл║л░Лѓ лЌл░л┐лЙЛђлЙлХЛїлх', 'What is mirror life? Scientists are sounding the alarm \r\nhttps://www.instagram.com/p/DMXc_pPMmra/ \r\nлњлЙлхлйлйЛІл╣ л░л┤л▓лЙл║л░Лѓ лЌл░л┐лЙЛђлЙлХЛїлх \r\n<img src=\"https://advokats-zp.com.ua/wp-content/uploads/elementor/thumbs/-%D0%90%D0%B4%D0%B2%D0%BE%D0%BA%D0%B0%D1%82-%D0%97%D0%B0%D0%BF%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B6%D1%8C%D0%B52-q192n6d7xksc1212xx6elpbd3ikmcvos3fzbn8ck80.webp\"> \r\n \r\n<a href=https://advokats-zp.com.ua/>лњлЙлхлйлйЛІл╣ л░л┤л▓лЙл║л░Лѓ лЌл░л┐лЙЛђлЙлХЛїлх</a> \r\nScientist Kate Adamala doesnРђЎt remember exactly when she realized her lab at the University of Minnesota was working on something potentially dangerous Рђћ so dangerous in fact that some researchers think it could pose an existential risk to all life forms on Earth. \r\n \r\nShe was one of four researchers awarded a $4 million US National Science Foundation grant in 2019 to investigate whether itРђЎs possible to produce a mirror cell, in which the structure of all of its component biomolecules is the reverse of whatРђЎs found in normal cells. \r\n \r\nThe work was important, they thought, because such reversed cells, which have never existed in nature, could shed light on the origins of life and make it easier to create molecules with therapeutic value, potentially tackling significant medical challenges such as infectious disease and superbugs. But doubt crept in. \r\n \r\nРђюIt was never one light bulb moment. It was kind of a slow boiling over a few months,РђЮ Adamala, a synthetic biologist, said. People started asking questions, she added, Рђюand we thought we can answer them, and then we realized we cannot.РђЮ \r\n \r\nThe questions hinged on what would happen if scientists succeeded in making a Рђюmirror organismРђЮ such as a bacterium from molecules that are the mirror images of their natural forms. Could it inadvertently spread unchecked in the body or an environment, posing grave risks to human health and dire consequences for the planet? Or would it merely fizzle out and harmlessly disappear without a trace?', '2025-11-07 04:57:54', '2025-11-07 04:57:54'),
